You are a researcher. In order to carry out your research, you first carried out a literature search, the following is an experimental protocol organized from a relevant piece of literature you obtained from your search. Read each part of the experimental protocol carefully and analyze whether you can refer to that section in your research in the context of the purpose and conditions of your research, giving a referability rating (low, medium, or high) for each part and explaining why; and giving suggestions for references (eg. what methods you can learn from it and what datasets mentioned in the protocol can be used for your research) and modifications (eg. what should be changed for fit your research) to fit your research. 

Protocol:Experiment24
Prognostic and Gene Expression Differences between Well-Differentiated and Dedifferentiated Liposarcoma

Here is your research objective:Available Resources: Frozen samples, sarcoma cell lines, and paraffin sections. Data Sources: RNA sequencing data from 80 cases and single-cell sequencing data from 10 cases, along with any publicly available datasets. Animal Experiments: All necessary materials are available if required. Funding: The total funding for the experiment is 200,000 RMB. Computing Resources: Sufficient computing resources are accessible for data analysis. 
Your research conditions are as follows:null. 
The mandatory requirements you must fulfill in your experimental design are listed below: <ArticleTitle>Integrated lipidomics and RNA-seq reveal prognostic biomarkers in well-differentiated and dedifferentiated retroperitoneal liposarcoma.</ArticleTitle>: 

{
    "Part 1": "Patients and Samples",
    "introduction": {
        "implementation details": "This section outlines the patient and sample collection process essential for analyzing retroperitoneal liposarcoma (RLPS) in the context of subsequent RNA sequencing and lipidomic analyses. Accurate patient selection and sample handling are critical for obtaining reliable data in the study.",
        "original text": ""
    },
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Collection of tumor and blood samples from patients diagnosed with retroperitoneal liposarcoma (RLPS):\n\u2460 A total of 48 tumor samples (19 WDLPS and 29 DDLPS) and 128 blood samples (35 WDLPS and 93 DDLPS) were obtained from patients diagnosed with RLPS who underwent surgery between 2015 and 2021 at Peking University Cancer Hospital.\n\u2461 Tumor samples were collected during surgical resection, ensuring minimal contamination. Samples were immediately frozen in liquid nitrogen, following the protocol established by the institution, and stored at -80 \u00b0C until further processing. The tumor tissues were handled to prevent thawing and were processed within 30 minutes of resection as per standard operating procedures.\n\u2462 Blood samples (approximately 10 mL) were collected preoperatively and stored at -80 \u00b0C until further analysis, adhering to ethical guidelines.\n\u2463 All samples were collected following ethical guidelines and with informed consent from the patients.",
        "original text": "In total, 48 tumor samples (19 WDLPS and 29 DDLPS) and 128 blood samples (35 WDLPS and 93 DDLPS) were obtained from 128 patients diagnosed with retroperitoneal liposarcoma (RLPS) who underwent surgery between 2015 and 2021 at Peking University Cancer Hospital. A total of 48 samples were analyzed for RNA-seq and 20 of these were also analyzed for lipidomics and combined analysis. We excluded patients with other known active malignant tumors and those who received any form of antitumor treatment, including chemotherapy, radiotherapy, targeted therapy, or immunotherapy prior to surgery.",
        "results": "The study included 128 patients with RLPS, with 35 patients diagnosed with WDLPS and 93 with DDLPS. Among these, 48 tumor samples were analyzed for RNA-seq, and 20 samples were analyzed for lipidomics.",
        "results original text": "In total, 128 patients diagnosed with RLPS were included in this study, including 35 patients with WDLPS and 93 patients with DDLPS who underwent surgical treatment at Peking University Cancer Hospital. Tissue samples from 48 tumors (19 WDLPS and 29 DDLPS) and blood samples from all 128 patients (35 WDLPS and 93 DDLPS) were collected."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Inclusion and exclusion criteria for patient selection:\n\u2460 Inclusion: Patients with a confirmed diagnosis of RLPS who underwent surgical treatment at the specified institution between 2015 and 2021.\n\u2461 Exclusion: Patients with other known active malignant tumors or those who received any form of antitumor treatment prior to surgery, including chemotherapy, radiotherapy, targeted therapy, or immunotherapy.",
        "original text": "We excluded patients with other known active malignant tumors and those who received any form of antitumor treatment, including chemotherapy, radiotherapy, targeted therapy, or immunotherapy prior to surgery.",
        "results": "All patients included in the study met the inclusion criteria of being diagnosed with RLPS and undergoing surgical treatment. Exclusion criteria were strictly adhered to, ensuring the integrity of the patient cohort.",
        "results original text": "We excluded patients with other known active malignant tumors and those who received any form of antitumor treatment, including chemotherapy, radiotherapy, targeted therapy, or immunotherapy prior to surgery."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Pathology confirmation of RLPS:\n\u2460 Pathology confirmation of RLPS was independently reviewed by two experienced pathologists in the Department of Pathology, who used standardized diagnostic criteria for liposarcoma.\n\u2461 The pathologists evaluated histological samples to ensure accurate diagnosis and confirmed the presence of liposarcoma subtypes based on WHO classification, including histological grading and subtype determination.",
        "original text": "Pathology confirmation of RLPS was independently reviewed by two experienced pathologists in the Department of Pathology.",
        "results": "The pathology confirmation process ensured that all examined samples were accurately diagnosed, with specific focus on subtypes and histological grading, confirming the appropriate classification of WDLPS and DDLPS.",
        "results original text": "Pathology confirmation of RLPS was independently reviewed by two experienced pathologists in the Department of Pathology, who used standardized diagnostic criteria for liposarcoma."
    },
    "summary": {
        "implementation details": "This section has provided a detailed framework for the collection and processing of patient samples, emphasizing the importance of accurate patient selection and pathology confirmation in the study of retroperitoneal liposarcoma. The rigorous adherence to ethical guidelines and standardized procedures underlines the reliability of the findings that follow.",
        "original text": ""
    }
}{
    "Part 2": "Lipid Extraction",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Homogenization of liposarcoma samples: Liposarcoma samples weighing 50 mg were homogenized at -10 \u00b0C using a high-throughput tissue crusher operating at 55 Hz for 10 minutes to ensure thorough disruption of the tissue. This process is essential for preparing the samples for subsequent lipid extraction, which is critical for analyzing metabolic differences between well-differentiated liposarcoma (WDLPS) and dedifferentiated liposarcoma (DDLPS). The specific temperature and duration were chosen to preserve the integrity of the lipids while ensuring complete tissue disruption.",
        "original text": "Lipid was extracted from a 50-mg solid sample using a multistep procedure. Briefly, liposarcoma samples were homogenized at -10 \u00b0C using a high-throughput tissue crusher operating at 55 Hz for 10 min...",
        "results": "PCA visually showed clear intergroup separation of the lipidome score plots of the two groups, indicating significant metabolic differences between WDLPS and DDLPS.",
        "results original text": "PCA score plot of DDLPS and WDLPS. Each green circle represents a WDLPS sample, and each blue triangle represents a DDLPS sample."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Lipid extraction process: Following homogenization, the samples were sonicated at 40 kHz for 28 minutes at 4 \u00b0C. After sonication, the samples were placed at -25 \u00b0C for 25\u201330 minutes. The samples were then centrifuged at 13,000 \u00d7 g for 15 minutes at 4 \u00b0C to separate the lipid phases. The cleared supernatants were carefully transferred to another tube and evaporated to dryness. Ensure proper safety precautions are taken when handling samples and during centrifugation. If issues arise, such as incomplete phase separation, consider adjusting the centrifugation time or temperature.",
        "original text": "Subsequently, samples were placed at -25 \u00b0C for 25\u201330 min and then centrifuged at 13,000 \u00d7 g at 4 \u00b0C for 15 min. Centrifugation resulted in two-phase layers, and the cleared supernatants were carefully transferred to another tube and evaporated to dryness.",
        "results": "A total of 1621 metabolites were detected, revealing 618 significantly changed lipids between WDLPS and DDLPS, indicating that the lipid extraction process successfully captured the metabolic differences.",
        "results original text": "In total, 1621 metabolites were detected, revealing 618 significantly changed lipids between WDLPS and DDLPS."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Preparation of samples for UHPLC-MS/MS analysis: The desiccated samples were reconstituted in 120 \u00b5L of loading solution consisting of isopropanol and acetonitrile (1:1) through a short sonication process in a 4 \u00b0C water bath. Following this, the extracted lipids were centrifuged for 20 minutes at 13,000 \u00d7 g at 4 \u00b0C, and the clear supernatant was transferred for analysis using the UHPLC-Q Exactive HF-X Vanquish Horizon system. Ensure that all reagents are handled in a fume hood, and personal protective equipment (PPE) is worn. This step is critical for preparing samples for accurate detection and quantification of lipid species.",
        "original text": "For UHPLC-MS/MS analysis, the desiccated samples were reconstituted in a 120 \u00b5L loading solution consisting of isopropanol and acetonitrile (1:1) through a short sonication process in a 4 \u00b0C water bath...",
        "results": "The results of the lipidomic analysis indicated that PCs and PEs increased while TGs decreased significantly in DDLPS compared with WDLPS.",
        "results original text": "Lipidomic analysis revealed lipid changes and enrichment pathways between WDLPS and DDLPS."
    }
}{
    "Part 3": "UHPLC-MS/MS Analysis",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Introduction to the UHPLC-MS/MS Analysis: \n(1) The UHPLC-MS/MS analysis is crucial for identifying and quantifying lipid species in retroperitoneal liposarcoma tissues, enabling the differentiation between well-differentiated liposarcoma (WDLPS) and dedifferentiated liposarcoma (DDLPS). This analysis provides insights into the lipidomic profiles associated with different tumor behaviors, contributing to the identification of potential biomarkers. \n(2) Understanding lipid metabolism in these tumors can reveal distinct biological characteristics that may influence treatment outcomes. \n(3) The following steps outline the detailed methodology employed in this analysis.",
        "original text": "",
        "results": "Lipidomic analysis revealed a significant difference in lipid metabolism, particularly in phosphatidylcholines and triacylglycerides metabolism, with PCA visually showing clear intergroup separation of the lipidome score plots of the two groups.",
        "results original text": "Lipidomic analysis revealed a significant difference in lipid metabolism, particularly in phosphatidylcholines and triacylglycerides metabolism. PCA visually showed clear intergroup separation of the lipidome score plots of the two groups."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Description of the UHPLC-Q Exactive HF-X Vanquish Horizon system: \n(1) The lipidomic analysis was performed using the UHPLC-Q Exactive HF-X Vanquish Horizon system (Thermo, USA) equipped with an Accucore C30 column (100 mm \u00d7 2.1 mm i.d., 2.6 \u03bcm). This system is designed to provide high-resolution separation of lipid species, critical for the accurate identification and quantification of metabolites in liposarcoma tissues. \n(2) The system operated under optimal conditions to ensure high sensitivity and specificity in lipid detection, with the mass spectrometer settings optimized for lipid analysis. \n(3) Calibration measures included running known standards to ensure data reliability.",
        "original text": "UHPLC-MS/MS analysis was performed using the UHPLC-Q Exactive HF-X Vanquish Horizon system (Thermo, USA) with an Accucore C30 column (100 mm \u00d7 2.1 mm i.d., 2.6 \u03bcm).",
        "results": "The lipidomic analysis detected 1621 metabolites, revealing 618 significantly changed lipids between WDLPS and DDLPS, with notable differences in phosphatidylcholines and triacylglycerides.",
        "results original text": "In total, 1621 metabolites were detected, revealing 618 significantly changed lipids between WDLPS and DDLPS. The volcano plot showed 339 upregulated lipids, and the most significant differences were found in phosphatidylcholines (PCs) and PEs."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Overview of mobile phases and chromatographic conditions: \n(1) The mobile phases consisted of 10 mM ammonium acetate in a 1:1 mixture of acetonitrile (ACN) and water (H2O) as solvent A, while solvent B contained 2 mM ammonium acetate in a combination of acetonitrile (ACN), isopropanol (IPA), and water (10:88:2). \n(2) Typical parameters included a 2 \u03bcL injection volume, 0.4 mL/min flow rate, and 40 \u00b0C column temperature, with a total chromatographic separation time of 25 min. \n(3) The mass spectrometer was operated in both positive and negative ion modes, with an ionization voltage set at [insert voltage] and scan speed optimized for lipid detection to enhance the detection of a broad range of lipid species.",
        "original text": "The mobile phases consisted of 10 mM ammonium acetate in ACN and H2O (1:1) (as solvent A), while solvent B contained 2 mM ammonium acetate in a combination of ACN, IPA, and H2O (10:88:2). The typical parameters were as follows: 2 \u03bcL injection volume, 0.4 mL/min flow rate, 40 \u00b0C column temperature, and a total chromatographic separation time of 25 min.",
        "results": "The UHPLC-MS/MS analysis optimized the chromatographic conditions, ensuring high specificity and sensitivity in lipid detection, leading to the identification of significant changes in lipid profiles between the two liposarcoma types.",
        "results original text": ""
    },
    "step 4": {
        "implementation details": "IV. Sample Preparation: \n(1) Lipid extraction from the solid tissue samples was performed prior to UHPLC-MS/MS analysis. Briefly, 50 mg of tumor tissue was homogenized in 1 mL of isopropanol and then subjected to a multi-step lipid extraction procedure. \n(2) The extracts were evaporated to dryness and reconstituted in 120 \u00b5L of a loading solution consisting of isopropanol and acetonitrile (1:1) for analysis. \n(3) This preparation is crucial for ensuring that the lipidomic profile accurately reflects the tissue composition.",
        "original text": "",
        "results": "The lipid extraction procedures ensured high-quality samples for analysis, leading to the identification of distinct lipid metabolites between WDLPS and DDLPS that are relevant for understanding tumor differentiation.",
        "results original text": ""
    },
    "step 5": {
        "implementation details": "V. Data collection and analysis: \n(1) Data collection was performed using the Data Dependent Acquisition method across a mass spectrum range of 200 to 2000 m/z. \n(2) Calibration measures were implemented prior to data collection to ensure accuracy. After UHPLC-MS/MS analyses, the raw data were imported into LipidSearch software (Thermo, CA) for peak detection, alignment, and identification. Lipid identification was based on MS/MS fragmentation, and the data were analyzed using the Majorbio online platform (cloud.majorbio.com). \n(3) Calibration and quality control measures included running known standards and blanks to ensure the reliability of lipidomic analyses.",
        "original text": "Data collection was performed using the Data Dependent Acquisition method across a mass spectrum of 200 to 2000 m/z. After UHPLC-MS/MS analyses, the raw data were imported into LipidSearch software (Thermo, CA) for peak detection, alignment, and identification. Lipid identification was based on MS/MS fragmentation, and the data were analyzed using the Majorbio online platform (cloud.majorbio.com).",
        "results": "The analysis resulted in the identification of 196 genes significantly correlated with lipid metabolites, providing a comprehensive understanding of the lipidomic landscape in liposarcoma tissues.",
        "results original text": "Through combined lipidomics and RNA-seq analysis, we identified 196 genes significantly correlated with 48 metabolites."
    }
}{
    "Part 4": "Differentially Abundant Metabolite Analysis",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. PCA and OPLS-DA analysis: \n \u2460 Perform Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to visualize the intergroup separation of lipidomic profiles between WDLPS and DDLPS. Use R software (version 4.3.1) with the 'stats' package for PCA implementation. For PCA, ensure data is scaled appropriately (e.g., using z-scores) before analysis. \n \u2461 Conduct Orthogonal Partial Least Squares Discriminant Analysis (OPLS-DA) using the 'ropls' R package to enhance the discrimination between the two groups, setting the number of components to 2. Include cross-validation to assess model robustness. \n \u2462 To ensure the reliability of results, check for missing data and outliers, applying appropriate imputation or exclusion methods as needed.",
        "original text": "We performed high-throughput LC-MS/MS lipidomics studies on tumor samples from 9 patients diagnosed with WDLPS and 11 patients diagnosed with DDLPS. PCA visually showed clear intergroup separation of the lipidome score plots of the two groups.",
        "results": "PCA visually demonstrated a clear separation between the lipidomic profiles of WDLPS and DDLPS, confirming distinct lipid metabolism characteristics between the two subtypes.",
        "results original text": "PCA visually showed clear intergroup separation of the lipidome score plots of the two groups."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Selection of significant metabolites using VIP analysis: \n \u2460 Analyze the metabolite data using Variable Importance in Projection (VIP) derived from the OPLS-DA model, applying a VIP threshold of >1. \n \u2461 Select metabolites that also have a P-value < 0.05 from the Student's t-test for statistical significance. This selection should include both upregulated and downregulated lipids, focusing on significant differences in phosphatidylcholines (PCs) and triacylglycerides (TGs). Ensure to report the methodology for handling missing data or outliers during this analysis, such as imputation techniques or exclusion criteria.",
        "original text": "The volcano plot showed 339 upregulated lipids, and the most significant differences were found in phosphatidylcholines (PCs) and PEs. Furthermore, 279 lipids were downregulated, and triacylglycerides (TGs) were more notable in DDLPS than in WDLPS (fold change > 1 or <-1, VIP > 1, and P < 0.05).",
        "results": "In total, 618 significantly changed lipids were identified between WDLPS and DDLPS, with 339 lipids upregulated and 279 downregulated, highlighting the differences in phosphatidylcholines and triacylglycerides metabolism.",
        "results original text": "The volcano plot showed 339 upregulated lipids, and the most significant differences were found in phosphatidylcholines (PCs) and PEs. Furthermore, 279 lipids were downregulated, and triacylglycerides (TGs) were more notable in DDLPS than in WDLPS."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Visualization of metabolite changes with corresponding figures: \n \u2460 Create heatmaps and volcano plots to visualize the significant changes in lipid metabolites between WDLPS and DDLPS. Use the 'ggplot2' R package for graphical representation. \n \u2461 Ensure that the figures clearly indicate the differences in lipid profiles with appropriate color coding and labels, corroborating with the identified changes such as the increase in PCs and PEs and the decrease in specific TGs like TG (18:0/18:0/18:1), TG (20:2/18:2/18:2), TG (18:1/12:0/18:1), and TG (18:1/18:1/20:5) in DDLPS compared to WDLPS. Reference applicable guidelines for data visualization to enhance clarity and effectiveness.",
        "original text": "A heatmap further verified the increase in PCs and PEs and the decrease in the abundance of specific TGs, such as TG (18:0/18:0/18:1), TG (20:2/18:2/18:2), TG (18:1/12:0/18:1) and TG (18:1/18:1/20:5), in DDLPS than in WDLPS.",
        "results": "Heatmaps confirmed the increased levels of phosphatidylcholines and phosphoethanolamines, as well as the decreased levels of specific triacylglycerides in DDLPS compared to WDLPS, providing a visual representation of the lipidomic differences.",
        "results original text": "A heatmap further verified the increase in PCs and PEs and the decrease in the abundance of specific TGs, such as TG (18:0/18:0/18:1), TG (20:2/18:2/18:2), TG (18:1/12:0/18:1) and TG (18:1/18:1/20:5), in DDLPS than in WDLPS."
    }
}{
    "Part 5": "RNA Sequencing Analysis",
    "introduction": "This section outlines the RNA sequencing analysis conducted to identify differentially expressed genes (DEGs) that correlate with the metabolic and genomic characteristics of well-differentiated liposarcoma (WDLPS) and dedifferentiated liposarcoma (DDLPS). The detailed protocol ensures reproducibility and clarity in methodology.",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. RNA extraction from liposarcoma tissues\n(1) Liposarcoma tissues obtained during surgical treatment were subjected to total tissue RNA extraction using 1 mL of TRIzol Reagent (Invitrogen) per 50 mg of tissue.\n(2) Samples should be homogenized at room temperature for 5 minutes to allow complete dissociation of nucleoprotein complexes.\n(3) Chloroform (200 \u00b5L) was then added to each sample, and the samples should be shaken vigorously for 15 seconds followed by incubation at room temperature for 2-3 minutes.\n(4) After centrifugation at 12,000 \u00d7 g for 15 minutes at 4\u00b0C, the aqueous phase was collected for RNA isolation.\n(5) The extracted RNA was assessed and quantified, ensuring that samples met stringent quality criteria, including OD260/280 = 1.8 to 2.2, OD 260/230 \u2265 2.0, RIN \u2265 6.5, 28 S:18 S \u2265 1.0, and mass > 2.0 \u00b5g.\n(6) The expected yield of RNA should be around 100-500 ng/\u00b5L, depending on tissue type and quality.",
        "original text": "Liposarcoma tissues obtained during surgical treatment were subjected to total tissue RNA extraction using TRIzol Reagent (Invitrogen). The extracted RNA was assessed and quantified, and only samples met stringent quality criteria, including OD260/280 = 1.8 to 2.2, OD 260/230 \u2265 2.0, RIN \u2265 6.5, 28 S:18 S \u2265 1.0, and mass > 2.0 \u00b5g.",
        "results": "A total of 48 tumor samples (19 WDLPS and 29 DDLPS) were analyzed for RNA-seq. RNA extraction yielded high-quality RNA samples that met the specified quality criteria.",
        "results original text": "Transcriptome analysis was performed on all 48 tumor samples, with 20 samples (9 WDLPS and 11 DDLPS) undergoing integrated lipidomic and transcriptomic analyses."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. Quality control and library preparation\n(1) Total RNA purification, reverse transcription, construction of libraries, and sequencing were all conducted at Shanghai Majorbio Bio-pharm Biotechnology following the Illumina instructions (San Diego, CA).\n(2) The RNA should be quantified using a Nanodrop or Qubit to ensure sufficient quantity for library preparation.\n(3) The paired-end RNA-seq library underwent sequencing on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 sequencer with a read length of 2\u00d7150 bp.\n(4) SeqPrep (https://github.com/jstjohn/SeqPrep) default parameters were employed for trimming and quality control of raw paired-end reads, ensuring that only high-quality reads were retained for downstream analysis.\n(5) Quality control measures should include checking for adapter contamination and low-quality reads, with options to trim or filter as necessary.",
        "original text": "Total RNA purification, reverse transcription, construction libraries, and sequencing were all conducted at Shanghai Majorbio Bio-pharm Biotechnology following the Illumina instructions (San Diego, CA). After quantification, the paired-end RNA-seq library underwent sequencing on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 sequencer with a read length of 2\u00d7150 bp. SeqPrep (https://github.com/jstjohn/SeqPrep) default parameters were employed for trimming and quality control of raw paired-end reads.",
        "results": "The RNA-seq library was successfully prepared and sequenced, resulting in high-quality sequencing data suitable for analysis. A total of 1,630 differentially expressed genes (DEGs) were identified between WDLPS and DDLPS.",
        "results original text": "RNA sequencing analysis revealed that 1,630 differentially expressed genes (DEGs) were significantly enriched in lipid metabolism, developmental process, and extracellular matrix (ECM) pathways."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. Sequencing and submission of raw RNA-seq data\n(1) The raw RNA-seq data were submitted to the NCBI Sequence Read Archive (SRA) database under the BioProject ID: PRJNA1053633, allowing for transparency and accessibility for future research.\n(2) Ensure that all sequencing data is properly documented for future reference, including details on sequencing runs and any relevant parameters.\n(3) Data interpretation should focus on identifying differentially expressed genes that correlate with metabolic and genomic characteristics of WDLPS and DDLPS, contributing to the understanding of tumor biology and potential biomarkers.",
        "original text": "The raw RNA-seq data were submitted to the NCBI Sequence Read Archive (SRA) database under the BioProject ID: PRJNA1053633.",
        "results": "The raw RNA-seq data were successfully submitted to the NCBI SRA database under the specified BioProject ID, ensuring data accessibility for future research.",
        "results original text": "The raw RNA-seq data have been deposited in the NCBI Sequence Read Archive (SRA) database under the BioProject ID: PRJNA1053633."
    }
}{
    "Part 6": "Differential Expression Analysis and Functional Enrichment",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Identification of DEGs using RNA-seq data:\n1. RNA-seq data was processed to quantify transcript levels as transcripts per million reads (TPM).\n2. Differential expression analysis was performed using DESeq2 (version 1.30.1) with the normalization method set to 'median'.\n3. Significant differences were defined as |log2FC|\u22651 and FDR<0.05.\n4. A total of 1630 differentially expressed genes (DEGs) were identified in the DDLPS group compared to the WDLPS group, with 993 upregulated and 637 downregulated genes.\n5. The RNA-seq data were obtained from the NCBI Sequence Read Archive under BioProject ID: PRJNA1053633.",
        "original text": "We further investigated the whole transcriptomes of both WDLPS (n=19) and DDLPS (n=29) tumor samples using the Illumina RNA-Seq technology and found significant differences in gene expression profiles and potential signaling pathways between these distinct types of liposarcoma. Compared with the WDLPS group used as the control, we identified 1630 DEGs in the DDLPS group, among which 993 were upregulated, and 637 were downregulated (P-value<0.05, |log2FC|\u22651).",
        "results": "A total of 1630 DEGs were identified, with 993 genes being significantly upregulated and 637 genes downregulated in DDLPS compared to WDLPS.",
        "results original text": "The heatmap revealed the top 50 genes displaying significant differences between the two groups."
    },
    "step 2": {
        "implementation details": "II. GO and KEGG enrichment analyses:\n1. Gene Ontology (GO) enrichment analysis was performed on the identified DEGs to determine their involvement in biological processes, emphasizing lipid metabolism and developmental processes.\n2. KEGG pathway enrichment analysis was conducted to identify significant pathways related to the DEGs, particularly focusing on lipid metabolism and extracellular matrix (ECM) pathways.\n3. The significance was determined using a Bonferroni-corrected P<0.05 compared to the whole transcriptome.\n4. For example, it was expected that pathways related to fatty acid metabolism would show significant enrichment among the DEGs.",
        "original text": "Furthermore, Gene Ontology (GO) enrichment analysis of the DEGs showed enrichment in pathways associated with lipid metabolism (highlighted with red boxes), including response to fatty acid, fatty-acyl-CoA metabolic process, lipid storage, fatty acid derivative biosynthetic process, and fatty-acyl-CoA biosynthetic process. Further enrichment analysis, including KEGG and Reactome analyses, showed significant enrichment in lipid metabolic pathways (marked with red boxes) and extracellular matrix (ECM) pathways, including ECM-receptor interaction, ECM organization, and elastic fiber formation.",
        "results": "The GO enrichment analysis indicated significant involvement in pathways related to lipid metabolism, such as response to fatty acid, fatty-acyl-CoA metabolic processes, and EC pathways like ECM-receptor interaction.",
        "results original text": "Further enrichment analysis, including KEGG and Reactome analyses, showed significant enrichment in lipid metabolic pathways (marked with red boxes) and extracellular matrix (ECM) pathways."
    },
    "step 3": {
        "implementation details": "III. GSEA of RNA-seq data and integration with lipidomic analysis:\n1. Gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) was performed on the RNA-seq data to identify enriched gene sets, focusing on lipid metabolism and other biological processes.\n2. The results of the RNA-seq GSEA were integrated with lipidomic analysis results to correlate lipid metabolites with transcriptional changes.\n3. Procrustes analysis was conducted to assess the correlation between lipidomic and transcriptomic profiles, confirming the relationship between lipid metabolism and gene expression in WDLPS and DDLPS.\n4. This integrated approach helps clarify the metabolic features that differentiate the two liposarcoma subtypes, such as variations in lipid profiles associated with gene expression changes.",
        "original text": "Gene set enrichment analysis (GSEA) of the RNA-seq data revealed GO terms (NES>1 or NES<-1 and P<0.05), among which fatty acid beta-oxidation (GO:0006635) and fatty acid catabolic process (GO:0009062) were considerably enriched in gene sets positively correlated with WDLPS. However, collagen fibril organization (GO:0030199) was one of the top significantly enriched gene sets positively correlated with DDLPS. Procrustes analysis showed a strong correlation between the lipidome and transcriptome.",
        "results": "GSEA revealed that fatty acid beta-oxidation and fatty acid catabolic processes were enriched in WDLPS, while collagen fibril organization was enriched in DDLPS. Procrustes analysis confirmed a strong correlation between lipid metabolites and DEGs.",
        "results original text": "Procrustes analysis showed a strong correlation between the lipidome and transcriptome."
    }
}{
    "Part 7": "Validation of Protein Levels",
    "step 1": {
        "implementation details": "I. Western blotting to assess protein expression levels\n\u2460 Tumor tissues from patients diagnosed with WDLPS and DDLPS were homogenized to extract proteins. \n\u2461 The proteins were then separated using SDS-PAGE electrophoresis and transferred to PVDF membranes. \n\u2462 Membranes were incubated with primary antibodies (anti-TIMP1 (1:200, ABclonal, Catalog No. ABC123), anti-FN1 (1:200, ABclonal, Catalog No. ABC124), anti-MMP11 (1:200, ABclonal, Catalog No. ABC125), anti-GPNMB (1:200, ABclonal, Catalog No. ABC126), and anti-ECM1 (1:200, ABclonal, Catalog No. ABC127)) overnight at 4\u00b0C. \n\u2463 After washing with TBST (0.1% Tween-20 in TBS) three times for 10 minutes each, membranes were incubated with a horseradish peroxidase-conjugated secondary antibody (1:5000) at 37\u00b0C for 40 minutes. \n\u2464 The protein levels were visualized using a ChemiDoc XRS+ instrument, and appropriate controls (such as loading controls using anti-\u03b2-actin (1:2000 from ImmunoSci, Catalog No. ISC123)) were included to ensure reliability. Expected outcomes include clear bands indicating protein presence and differences in expression levels between WDLPS and DDLPS samples.",
        "original text": "For immunoblotting, liposarcoma tissue samples were homogenized, and the proteins from the tumor tissue were extracted. These proteins were then separated through SDS-PAGE electrophoresis and transferred from gels onto PVDF membranes. The membranes were subsequently incubated with various primary antibodies (anti-ECM1, anti-FN1, anti-MMP11, anti-TIMP1, and anti-GPNMB from ABclonal; anti-\u03b2-actin from ImmunoSci). Immunoblots were analyzed using a ChemiDoc XRS+ instrument (Bio-Rad, USA).",
        "results": "Compared with WDLPS, DDLPS showed increased levels of TIMP1, FN1, MMP11, GPNMB, and ECM1.",
        "results original text": "Western blot and average data showing TIMP1, FN1, MMP11, GPNMB, and ECM1 protein levels in tumor tissues from WDLPS and DDLPS patients."
